<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>🔀 RS001 Week 9 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Cause and Effect — Enemies Appear · <strong>Course:</strong> Text Adventure (Python) · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week is about thinking through how one choice changes what happens next. <code>if</code> / <code>else</code> lets different code run depending on the player's path — so the <strong>left</strong> road meets a goblin and the <strong>right</strong> road meets an orc. You will read branching code, fix broken code on paper, and explain in your own words how a choice causes an effect.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>🧠 Words to know: <strong>if</strong>, <strong>else</strong>, <strong>elif</strong>, <strong>branch</strong>, <strong>cause</strong>, <strong>effect</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<pre><code class="language-python">path = game.ask(&quot;Which way? (left/right)&quot;).strip().lower()
if path == &quot;left&quot;:
    enemy = &quot;goblin&quot;
else:
    enemy = &quot;orc&quot;
game.say(f&quot;A {enemy} appears!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. In your head, work out what happens, then write your answer.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">path = &quot;left&quot;
if path == &quot;left&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;cave&quot;)
else:
    game.say(&quot;field&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Which word is printed?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">paths = [&quot;left&quot;, &quot;right&quot;]
enemies = [&quot;goblin&quot;, &quot;orc&quot;]
path = &quot;right&quot;
if path == paths[0]:
    game.say(enemies[0])
elif path == paths[1]:
    game.say(enemies[1])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Which enemy is printed, and which branch ran?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">path = &quot;up&quot;
if path == &quot;left&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;goblin&quot;)
elif path == &quot;right&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;orc&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The player typed <code>"up"</code>. What appears on screen?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, fix it on paper, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — Left should give a goblin and right should give an orc. Right now <strong>both</strong> paths give a goblin.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">path = game.ask(&quot;way?&quot;).strip().lower()
if path == &quot;left&quot;:
    enemy = &quot;goblin&quot;
if path == &quot;right&quot;:
    enemy = &quot;goblin&quot;
game.say(f&quot;A {enemy} appears!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the second branch has the wrong enemy.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — The second branch should be an <code>elif</code>, not a fresh <code>if</code>, so the two choices are linked as one decision.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">path = game.ask(&quot;way?&quot;).strip().lower()
if path == &quot;left&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;A goblin blocks the cave.&quot;)
else path == &quot;right&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;An orc roams the field.&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the word after the first branch should be <code>elif</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The enemy's name and HP should come from the <strong>same</strong> index. Here the name is from the left path but the HP is from the right.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">paths = [&quot;left&quot;, &quot;right&quot;]
enemies = [&quot;goblin&quot;, &quot;orc&quot;]
enemy_hp = [10, 25]
path = &quot;left&quot;
if path == paths[0]:
    game.say(f&quot;{enemies[0]} (HP {enemy_hp[1]})&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> match the index across all three lists.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Read this working example. The player chooses a path, and the choice decides which enemy appears.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">path = game.ask(&quot;Which way? (left/right)&quot;).strip().lower()
if path == &quot;left&quot;:
    enemy = &quot;goblin&quot;
    game.say(&quot;A goblin blocks the cave.&quot;)
elif path == &quot;right&quot;:
    enemy = &quot;orc&quot;
    game.say(&quot;An orc roams the field.&quot;)
else:
    enemy = &quot;shadow&quot;
    game.say(&quot;A shadow waits on an unknown road.&quot;)
game.say(f&quot;A {enemy} appears!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What does <code>.strip().lower()</code> do to the player's answer, and why is that helpful here?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Which branch runs if the player types <code>right</code>? Which line of <code>enemy =</code> runs?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>When does the <code>else</code> branch run?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>The choice is the cause. What is the effect of choosing <code>left</code>?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does the last <code>game.say(...)</code> line run no matter which path the player picks?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Explain Your Lesson Code 🎥</h2>
<p>In today's live lesson you wrote branching code for your own game. Make a short video on your phone (or a parent's phone) explaining the code you wrote. You may show it running. Teach it like the viewer has never coded, and use these words: <strong>if</strong>, <strong>else</strong>, <strong>branch</strong>, <strong>cause</strong>, <strong>effect</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Show the <code>if</code> / <code>else</code> code you wrote and read it out loud.</li>
<li>Explain which branch runs when the player goes left, and which runs when they go right.</li>
<li>Point out the cause (the choice) and the effect (the enemy that appears).</li>
<li>Show it running once for each path so the effect is clear.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
